		<text>
		<body>
		<pb n="1"/>
		
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Denekamp</placeName>&#44;&#8212; <date>15&#44; 1847&#40;1&#41;</date>.</p>
			<p><addressee>Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee>&#44; <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>&#44;</p>
			<p>Very much beloved brother&#45;in&#45;law&#58;</p>

		  <p rend="indent(1)">In the hope that these lines will find you in the same state<lb/> of health in which they leave us&#44; and that we hear the same thing from<lb/> each other for many years to come&#44; amen.  As regards my dear children&#44;<lb/> in the matter of their studies&#44; everything seems to be going well.<lb/>  And they are&#44; thank God&#44; all as fresh and happy as fish in water.  My<lb/> oldest daughter&#44; <persName>Sarah</persName>&#44; always says&#44; &#34;I wish I could see my <persName>Uncle Itsik</persName><lb/> again&#40;&#63;&#41;.  <sic>with</sic> regard to business&#44; however&#44; everything here is very<lb/> bad.  Everything is fine but the cost of living is high.  This affects<lb/> business badly&#44; and whoever has a small sum goes to <placeName>America</placeName>.  Unfortunate&#45;<lb/>ly&#44; I had a partner who cheated me very badly.  I lost a thousand thalers<lb/> through him&#44; and&#44; in addition to that&#44; I had to stand for a bankruptcy<lb/> in <placeName>BREHM</placeName>&#44; to the extent of 500 thalers.  Thus my business affairs are<lb/> in poor condition to earn a living for my dear wife and children.  I<lb/> must nowadays keep busy and earn little.  That is why I take the liber&#45;<lb/>ty to ask you whether you could not spare $200 or $300 which I shall<lb/> repay you in 3 years&#44; or&#44; should it be the case that an inheritance<lb/> from our uncle&#44; may he rest in peace&#44; or from our aunt&#44; be forthcoming<lb/> to us&#44; you can retain it.  I do not want to make you lose a penny&#44;<lb/> God forbid&#44; I do this simply to be able to support my dear wife and all<lb/> children in honor.  If you cannot or do not want to&#44; then please&#44;<lb/> when you write&#44; say nothing about this to <persName>Leah</persName>&#44; that I have asked you<lb/> for this.  For my dear wife might&#44; God forbid&#44; be troubled by this&#44; and<lb/> I might be sorry for it.  She has altogether too much of a sense of<lb/> honor.  By the life of this writer&#44; she knows nothing about this.  I<lb/> have simply told her that I have written to you from <placeName>Bremen</placeName>.  My dear<lb/> wife and children will soon write to you themselves.  Please send you<lb/> answer soon.  I hope that you will always write frequently&#44; for my<lb/> dear wife is always anxious about you when you do not write.  I know<lb/> of no further news to write but do not forget to write frequently.</p>

		<pb n="2"/>
		
			<p>My <persName>Lippman</persName> and my <persName>Sarah</persName> always say&#44; &#34;When we are big&#44; we shall travel to<lb/> our <persName>Uncle Itsik</persName> in <placeName>America</placeName>&#34;.  I know of nothing further to write.</p>
			<p>I remain&#44;</p>
		  <p rend="indent(6)">Your devoted brother&#45;in&#45;law&#44;</p>
		  <p rend="indent(6)"><persName>Zvi</persName>&#44; son of <persName>Jacob</persName>&#44;</p>
		  <p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">H. I. Elkus</persName></p>

			<p>My dear wife and children greet you many times and hope to hear from<lb/> you very soon.</p>
		</body>
